The particle content of this gauge $U(1)_X$ extension of the supersymmetric 
standard model is fixed.  Whereas certain interactions are mandatory, 
others are not.  As explained in Ref.~\cite{m02}, different models come 
from choosing one of two classes of solutions: (A) or (B).  For each, 
there is also the ratio of two charges which may vary.  Hence there 
are many possible models within this framework.  Each will have all the 
mandatory interactions required to explain the 750 GeV observation, but 
will have different predictions regarding other phenomena.

\section{Generic Solutions of Classes (A) and (B)}

Consider the gauge group $SU(3)_C \times
SU(2)_L \times U(1)_Y \times U(1)_X$ with the particle content of 
Ref.~\cite{m02} as shown in Table 1.  There are three copies of 
$Q,u^c,d^c,L,e^c,N^c,S_1,S_2$; two copies of $U,U^c,S_3$; and one copy of 
$\phi_1,\phi_2,D,D^c$.
The following terms of the superpotential are always allowed:
\begin{eqnarray}
&& Q u^c \phi_2, ~~~ Q d^c \phi_1, ~~~ L e^c \phi_1, ~~~ L N^c \phi_2, ~~~ 
S_3 \phi_1 \phi_2, \\ 
&& S_3 U U^c, ~~~ S_3 D D^c, ~~~ S_1 S_2 S_3.
\end{eqnarray}
The charges $n_1$ and $n_4$ are arbitrary, except that $3n_1+n_4 \neq 0$ 
is required to forbid the $\mu \phi_1 \phi_2$ term of the minimal 
supersymmetric standard model (MSSM).  
